<section id="about" class="fade-in">
  <span class="sec-lbl" id="lAbout">About Haryana</span>
  <h2 class="sec-title" id="aboutTitle">Where the <em>Mahabharata Was Born</em></h2>
  <p class="sec-body" id="aboutBody">Haryana — the land whose name means "abode of Hari (Vishnu)" or "green land" (Hari = green, ayana = abode) — is one of the most consequential pieces of land in human history. The Kurukshetra district is the site of the Mahabharata war — the eighteen-day battle between the Pandavas and Kauravas that the Bhagavad Gita describes as having taken place on this very soil. Here, Lord Krishna delivered the Bhagavad Gita to Arjuna before the battle — one of the most influential philosophical texts in human civilization. The Harappan Civilization thrived on Haryana's banks: Rakhigarhi in Hisar district is the largest Harappan site yet discovered, larger than Mohenjo-daro, with an unbroken 5,000-year archaeological sequence. Haryana also hosts Thanesar — the capital of Harshavardhana's empire (606–647 AD), the most powerful ruler of North India before the Islamic invasions. The state was carved from Punjab in 1966 following linguistic reorganization and has since transformed itself with extraordinary speed. The Green Revolution was pioneered here — Haryana's farmers adopted high-yield wheat varieties in the 1960s and transformed India from a famine-stricken country into a wheat exporter. Today Haryana contributes over 60% of India's wheat procurement. In sports, Haryana is the most dominant state in India: the state that is 1.7% of India's population has won over 40% of India's Olympic medals since 2000 — in wrestling, boxing, weightlifting, hockey and athletics. The state has produced 40+ Olympic and World Championship medalists. The Aravalli hills in the south, the Ghaggar river in the north, the Yamuna in the east and the Shivalik foothills create a diverse landscape beneath Haryana's flat exterior. The state's folk culture — Ragini, Saang theatre, Phag songs, Holi of Brij — is robustly alive in villages where farmers are also Olympic champions.</p>
</section>
