{emoji:"🦅",name:"Sultanpur National Park",location:"Gurugram District",desc:"A small but extraordinarily rich bird sanctuary — 150+ species including the endangered Sarus crane, bar-headed goose and 40+ migratory species visiting in winter. Located just 15 km from Gurugram, Sultanpur is where the NCR's urban millions escape to watch 5,000+ flamingos turn the wetland pink at dawn. One of India's most accessible and rewarding birdwatching sites.",fee:["Rs.5 Indians","Rs.40 Foreigners"]},
{emoji:"🌊",name:"Brahma Sarovar — Kurukshetra",location:"Kurukshetra",desc:"The largest man-made tank in India — a sacred lake of extraordinary sanctity, believed to have been created by Brahma himself. A 3.3 km embankment dotted with 56 temples surrounds the shimmering water. During solar eclipses (Surya Grahan), millions of pilgrims bathe here simultaneously — one of the most spectacular mass pilgrimage events in the world. At dusk the reflections of the temples in the still water are breathtaking.",fee:["Free"]},
{emoji:"🏰",name:"Pinjore Gardens (Yadavindra Gardens)",location:"Panchkula District",desc:"One of North India's finest Mughal-period gardens — terraced gardens built by Nawab Fidai Khan in the 17th century on a hillside in the Shivalik foothills. Seven terraces descend with fountains, pavilions, a Japanese garden and a mini zoo. In spring when the flowers bloom and the Shivalik hills frame the backdrop, Pinjore is one of Haryana's most beautiful places.",fee:["Rs.20 Indians"]},
{emoji:"🦌",name:"Kalesar National Park",location:"Yamunanagar District",desc:"A dense sal and bamboo forest in the Shivalik foothills — home to leopards, elephants, elephants (migratory from Uttarakhand), sloth bears, barking deer, king cobra and over 200 bird species. The Yamuna river forms the northern boundary. The forest is dense, wild and almost entirely untouched by tourism — offering genuine wilderness experience within 3 hours of Delhi.",fee:["Paid"]},
{emoji:"🛕",name:"Sthaneshwar Mahadev & Heritage Circuit",location:"Kurukshetra",desc:"The ancient Sthaneshwar Mahadev temple — where the Pandavas worshipped Shiva before the great battle — is one of the most sacred sites in Kurukshetra's extensive heritage circuit. The circuit includes the Bhadrakali Temple, Sheikh Chilli's Tomb, Sannihit Sarovar (where the seven sacred rivers are believed to converge) and the Jyotisar pipal tree under which the Bhagavad Gita was spoken.",fee:["Free"]},
