const cuisinesData=[
{emoji:"🥛",name:"Haryanvi Cuisine — Dairy Heart",region:"Statewide — Milk & Butter Tradition",desc:"Haryana is India's dairy heartland — the state has the highest per capita milk production in India. This abundance shapes every meal: butter (makhan) is added to everything, lassi is thick as cream, kadhi is made with fresh buttermilk, and the ghee used in chapati is the best-quality desi ghee in North India. The Haryanvi farmer's relationship to the cow and buffalo shapes the entire food culture."},
{emoji:"🫓",name:"Bajra Khichdi & Millet Rotis",region:"Rural Haryana",desc:"The traditional winter staple of Haryana's villages — pearl millet (bajra) cooked as khichdi with ghee, or ground and made into thick flat rotis (bajra roti) eaten with jaggery and white butter. A nutritional powerhouse that has sustained generations of farmers and wrestlers. Bajra is Haryana's native grain — drought-resistant, iron-rich and deeply flavored. The simplicity of bajra roti with makhan and gur is transcendent."},
{emoji:"🥣",name:"Kadhi Pakora — Haryana Style",region:"Statewide",desc:"Haryana's kadhi is thicker, more sour and more generous than the standard North Indian version — a yogurt and besan curry with large fried pakoras, served over rice or with bajra roti. The buttermilk used is fresh from the morning's churning. Haryanvi women consider their kadhi recipe a point of personal pride. Eaten at every family gathering, it is comfort food of the most fundamental kind."},
{emoji:"🌾",name:"Bathua Raita & Seasonal Greens",region:"Winter Special — Statewide",desc:"Bathua (Chenopodium) — a wild leafy green that grows in wheat fields — is Haryana's signature winter food. Bathua raita (yogurt mixed with boiled bathua), bathua paratha and bathua saag are eaten through winter with extraordinary enthusiasm. Other seasonal greens — sarson (mustard), methi (fenugreek) and palak — are cooked with maize flour and fresh butter in a cuisine deeply tied to the agricultural calendar."},
{emoji:"🍵",name:"Thick Lassi & Chaach",region:"Statewide",desc:"Haryana's lassi is not the restaurant variety — it is a meal in itself. Thick, freshly churned yogurt blended with water until frothy, topped with a thick layer of malai (cream), sometimes with a ball of white butter floating on top. Served in large clay pots. The Haryanvi farmer's morning begins with this lassi. Chaach (spiced thin buttermilk) is drunk through the day. No beverage in India is more generously poured."},
{emoji:"🍛",name:"Hara Dhania Shorba & Haryanvi Dal",region:"Statewide",desc:"Green coriander soup — a thin, fragrant broth of fresh coriander, green chilies and garlic — is a uniquely Haryanvi preparation drunk before meals as a digestive and palate primer. The Haryanvi mixed dal — arhar, chana and masoor lentils cooked together with whole spices and finished with a mustard-seed tempering — is the everyday backbone of the rural diet, eaten twice daily with millet or wheat rotis."},
{emoji:"🍬",name:"Gajar Ka Halwa & Milk Sweets",region:"Winter Special",desc:"Carrot halwa made from Haryana's famous red Desi Gajar (native red carrot available only in winter) — grated, slow-cooked in milk with sugar and enormous amounts of ghee. The Haryanvi version is richer and less sweet than the standard version. Rewari's sweet shops produce extraordinary milk-based sweets using the state's surplus milk: kalakand, khoya barfi, and peda that rival any in North India."},
{emoji:"🫕",name:"Kachri Ki Sabzi & Sangri",region:"South Haryana — Aravalli Border",desc:"In the Mewat and southern Haryana districts bordering Rajasthan, the desert food traditions enter — kachri (wild desert melon, dried) and sangri (dried desert beans) cooked with spices create uniquely flavored curries impossible to find elsewhere. These are drought-season foods of extraordinary ingenuity — transforming dried produce into deeply satisfying curries that sustained communities through hot, waterless summers."},
{emoji:"🥚",name:"Haryanvi Non-Veg — Village Style",region:"Rural Haryana",desc:"The non-vegetarian tradition of Haryana's villages centers on desi chicken (free-range country chicken) cooked in a dry masala over wood fire — no water, just onion, ginger, garlic and whole spices releasing their own moisture. The village murgh is dramatically different from commercial chicken. Mutton preparations in Mewat use local herbs and a slower cook. The food is bold, spare and entirely satisfying."}
